Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and halve @zucchini{1}, cut crosswise into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons. Trim and slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 1⁄2 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

While pasta cooks, rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water, then pat dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once pasta has cooked for 5 minutes, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Add zucchini, scallion whites, and garlic; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened and lightly browned, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Stir in shrimp, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @marinara sauce{14%ounce}, and 1⁄4 cup reserved pasta cooking water. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer.

> If pasta isn't done cooking yet, ladle pasta water directly from pot.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp are opaque and cooked through and zucchini is tender, ~{3-4%minutes}.

To pan with shrimp, add drained spaghetti and @butter{1%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until butter has melted and everything is coated in sauce, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> If sauce seems too thick, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time. For extra richness, finish pasta with a drizzle of olive oil.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide pasta between shallow #bowls{}. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.